## 3. Review of Related Literature (RRL)

### Dynamic Pricing & Machine Learning in Aviation
The airline industry has historically relied on revenue management systems grounded in static, rule-based logic. However, recent academic studies emphasize the shift towards machine learning (ML) models for dynamic pricing. According to research, regression algorithms—particularly Gradient Boosting Regressors and Random Forest models—are highly effective at forecasting ticket prices by analyzing multi-dimensional features such as advance booking days, route popularity, and seasonal fluctuations. These predictive models allow airlines to optimize yield management in volatile markets, shifting from reactive historical analysis to proactive price adjustments based on real-time willingness-to-pay estimations. Furthermore, modern PSS implementations extend these ML pricing models beyond base airfares to encompass ancillary services (e.g., baggage and seat selection), enabling personalized, context-based bundling strategies akin to the "Fare Families" approach used in modern e-commerce platforms.

### Concurrency Control in High-Demand Reservation Systems
Preventing overbooking and maintaining data consistency is a critical challenge in distributed travel reservation architectures. Academic literature frequently examines the trade-offs between optimistic and pessimistic concurrency control mechanisms for inventory management (seat locking). While optimistic locking yields higher throughput in low-contention environments, pessimistic locking is the preferred standard for reservation systems where double-booking must be strictly prevented. Pessimistic control operates by assuming conflicts will occur; thus, it enforces a lock on the resource (e.g., via `SELECT ... FOR UPDATE` in SQL databases) before the transaction begins. To mitigate the performance bottlenecks inherent in blocking transactions, modern architectures often hybridize the approach: employing transient "soft locks" or distributed caching mechanisms (like Redis) during the user's browsing phase, and falling back to stringent pessimistic row-level database locks only during final checkout. This dual-layer algorithm ensures both a fluid user experience and strict backend data integrity.

